Tracking Food Equipment: SSS Grows, But Traffic Still Weak

We track restaurant data as a leading indicator for MIDD's Commercial Foodservice business. Data trends support the weaker sales outlook (Mgmt. guiding to a \(2 - 3\%\) sales decline in 3Q) as traffic remained weak and consumer surveys showed lower discretionary spending.

Bottom Line. Expectations have taken a step- down since the start of the year with MIDD looking for Commercial Foodservice sales of \(580 - 590m\) in 3Q25, and step up slightly in 4Q, implying \(\sim\) LSD- MSD Y/Y organic sales decline in 2H25 (we model a \(\sim 3\%\) organic decline). This weaker outlook is consistent with data trends, with continued weakness in traffic and fewer new expected restaurant openings.

SSS Increases. We analyze US restaurant SSS as a key driver for MIDD sales. July QSR SSS increased \(1.4\%\) Y/Y (up 30bps in June) as check size grew \(1.4\%\) Y/Y while traffic was flat Y/Y. The Jefferies Restaurant team noted that promotional intensity heading into the summer is likely driving traffic, but weighing slightly on mix. The team believes that the demand for dining out occasions could sustain and support LSD SSS growth for the broader industry in the near term (link).
Exhibit 1 - July QSR SSS increased \(1.4\%\) Y/Y
Source: Guest XM, powered by Black Box Intelligence
Exhibit 2 - July QSR Traffic was flat Y/Y while check size increased \(1.4\%\) Y/Y
Source: Guest XM, powered by Black Box Intelligence

SSS Outlook Weakens, Traffic Remains Weak. The July NRA index decreased modestly (down 30bps), with operators continuing to report higher sales but lower traffic. Operators reported a net increase in SSS in July, but slightly lower than in June, with net \(6\%\) reporting sales growth (vs. \(8\%\) in June). Customer traffic continues to decline but at a more moderated rate, with net \(6\%\) operators reporting traffic decline (vs. net \(11\%\) in June). Operators are less optimistic about sales growth in 6M, with only net \(2\%\) them expecting growth (vs. prev. \(11\%\) ). Despite a weak traffic environment, more than half of operators (53%) continued to make an investment in equipment, expansion, or remodeling in the last three months, the highest reading in 13 months. This trend is expected to continue with \(55\%\) of operators looking to make capex for equipment, expansion, or remodeling in the next 6M.
Exhibit 3 - July current SSS index declined 20bps M/ M
Exhibit 4 - July SSS Expectation Index increased 89bps M/M

Chains Continue to Expect Unit Growth. Chains have generally maintained new unit development plans with WEN and MCD on track, and FWRG is expecting double- digit growth in new openings in 2026. EAT noted that the new TurboChef installed in the kitchen improves efficiency and reliability. Our unit tracker as of 2Q25 supports chain expansion plans, with the average net unit growth for large chain restaurants expected to be \(2\%\) in 2025 and 2026 (vs. \(0 - 2\%\) growth range seen before 2024).
Exhibit 5 - Most restaurants are expecting to have solid net unit growth in 2025 and 2026
Source: Company Data and Jefferies
Exhibit 6 - Chain Commentaries from 2Q25

CompanyCommentaryNOLsYear-end data through the second quarter, we closed 9 company-owned restaurants. 13 closures are expected in the third quarter with the balance of the expected closures occurring in the fourth quarter. In addition, we expect to close 12 to 17 company-owned restaurants in 2026. Turning to the rest of our full year guidance for 2025, weâ€™re revising our expectations based on recent trends.WENFirst is net unit growth. We have opened 118 new restaurants in the first half of the year, and we remain on track to deliver between 2% to 3% net new unit growth for the full year.TKHRDuring the second quarter, we opened four company-owned restaurants, including two Bubba's 33 locations, and we remain on track to open approximately 30 company-owned restaurants this year.MCDFinally, we remain on pace to open approximately 2,200 restaurants globally this year and continue to target about 1/4 of these openings to be in our U.S. and IOM segment. We expect to open more than 1,600 restaurants in our IOM markets, including about 1,000 in China. In total, we continue to expect slightly over 4% unit growth from the nearly 1,800 net restaurant additions in 2025.YUMMoving towards a significant event. We opened 871 gross new units in the quarter, largely consistent with Q2 of last year and translating to 386 net new units. At KFC, we opened 566 gross new units across 58 countries, fueled by China, India and Japan. We feel good about the development momentum with the long-term global white space remaining highly attractive, particularly in Europe and East Asia, where the opportunity is vast.FWRGFor 2025, we are targeting 62 to 67 new locations. The broad geographic diversity of our new restaurant openings can be seen in the first half of this year, where we opened new restaurants in 18 markets across 15 states. In fact, our double-digit percentage growth plans for 2026 are already firmly in place, and we are nearly halfway to our target for 2027.EATWe continue to hear from the restaurant teams that TurboChef put out way less heat in the kitchen, cooks more evenly and quickly are more reliable and easier to clean than the old equipment.
Source: Factset Equipment Pricing. July Commercial cooking and food warming equipment PPI was up \(5\%\) Y/Y and 36bps M/M.
Exhibit 7 - July Commercial cooking and food warming equipment PPI increased 5.1% Y/Y and 36bps M/M

Consumer Confidence Survey Points to Lower Discretionary Spending The August Consumer Confidence Index has remained relatively consistent this summer, with concerns about tariffs and higher inflation. At 97, the current reading is roughly halfway between the Nov. 2024 highs of 113 and the 86 reading that occurred following the Liberation Day in April. Discretionary spending intentions, including dining out, decreased. August Michigan consumer sentiment decreased 3.5pts M/M, the first decline in four months largely driven by inflation worries.
Exhibit 8 - Aug. Consumer Confidence Index decreased 1.3pts M/M
Source: The Conference Board
Exhibit 9 - Aug. Consumer Present and Future Indexes decreased 1.6pts M/M and 1.2pts M/M, respectively
Source: The Conference Board
